FORMULA.STRTODATE: Returns Date a Datetime object using a string date in addition to the date format
FORMULA.DATESUBTRACT: Apply a substract operation on a Date or Datetime, it can substract one or several years, months, days, hours, minutes and seconds
FORMULA.DATEADD: Apply a add operation on a Date or Datetime, it can add one or several years, months, days, hours, minutes or seconds
FORMULA.DATEVALUE: Converts a date in the text format to a serial number that represents a date.
FORMULA.DATEVALUE-OPT: date:A valid date in text format
FORMULA.DAY: Returns a day of the month as an integer from 1 to 31.
FORMULA.DAY-OPT: date:A valid date in text format
FORMULA.DAYS: Returns the numero of days between two dates
FORMULA.DAYS-OPT: start_date:A valid date to start filter;end_date:A valid date to end filter

FORMULA.DAYS360-OPT: start_date:A valid date to start filter;end_date:A valid date to end filter;method:The type of day count basis to use. FALSE (default) is US method, TRUE is European method.
FORMULA.EDATE: Returns the serial number of the date that is the specified number of months before of after the start date.
FORMULA.EDATE-OPT: start_date:A valid date to start filter;months:number of months before of after start_date
FORMULA.EOMONTH: Returns the date of the last day of the month before or after a specified number of months
FORMULA.EOMONTH-OPT: start_date:A valid date to start filter;months:number of months before of after start_date
FORMULA.HOUR: Returns the hour of the day as an integer from 0 to 23.
FORMULA.MINUTE: Returns the minute of the hour as an integer from 0 to 59.
FORMULA.ISOWEEKNUM: Returns number of the ISO week number of the year for a given date.
FORMULA.ISOWEEKNUM-OPT: date:A valid date in text format
FORMULA.MONTH: Returns the month of the year as an integer from 1 to 12.
FORMULA.MONTH-OPT: date:A valid date in text format
FORMULA.NETWORKDAYS: Returns the number of weekdays between two dates that you specify. It automatically excludes weekend days.
FORMULA.NETWORKDAYS-OPT: start_date:A valid date in text format;end_date:A valid date in text format;holidays: A list of non-work days as dates
FORMULA.NETWORKDAYSINTL: Returns the number of whole workdays between two dates using parameters to indicate which and how many days are weekend days. Weekend days and any days that are specified as holidays are not considered as workdays.
FORMULA.NETWORKDAYSINTL-OPT: start_date:A valid date in text format;end_date:A valid date in text format;weekend:Settings for which days of the week sould be considerated weekends (default 1);holidays: A list of non-work days as dates
FORMULA.NOW: NOW() returns the serial number of the current date and time
FORMULA.SECOND: Returns the second of the minute as an integer from 0 to 59.
FORMULA.SECOND-OPT: date:A valid date in text format
FORMULA.TIME: Returns the decimal number for a particular time. If the cell format was General before the function was entered, the result is formatted as a date.
FORMULA.TIME-OPT: hour:The hour for the time your wish to create;minute:The minute for the time your wish create;second:The second for the time you wish create
FORMULA.TIMEVALUE: Returns the decimal number of the time represented by a text string. The decimal number is a value ranging from 0 (zero) to 0.99988426, representing the times from 0:00:00 (12:00:00 AM) to 23:59:59 (11:59:59 P.M.).
FORMULA.TODAY: Returns the serial number of the current date.
FORMULA.WEEKDAY: Returns the day of the week corresponding to a date. The day is given as an integer, ranging from 1 (Sunday) to 7 (Saturday), by default.
FORMULA.WEEKDAY-OPT: date:A valid date in text format;return_type:A number representing day of week mapping schema
FORMULA.YEAR: Returns the year corresponding to a date. The year is returned as an integer in the range 1900-9999.
FORMULA.YEAR-OPT: date:A valid date in text format
FORMULA.WEEKNUM: Returns the week number of a specific date. For example, the week containing January 1 is the first week of the year, and is numbered week 1.
FORMULA.WEEKNUM-OPT: date:A valid date in text format;return_type:the day the week begins. default is 1
FORMULA.WORKDAY: Returns a number that represents a date that is the indicated number of working days before or after a date (the starting date). Working days exclude weekends and any dates identified as holidays. Use WORKDAY to exclude weekends or holidays when you calculate invoice due dates, expected delivery times, or the number of days of work performed.
FORMULA.WORKDAY-OPT: start_date:A valid date in text format;days:The working days before of after start date;holidays:A list dates that should be considered non-work days
FORMULA.WORKDAYINTL: Returns the serial number of the date before or after a specified number of workdays with custom weekend parameters. Weekend parameters indicate which and how many days are weekend days. Weekend days and any days that are specified as holidays are not considered as workdays.
FORMULA.WORKDAYINTL-OPT: start_date:A valid date in text format;days:The working days before of after start date;weekend:Setting for which days of the week should be considered weekends;holidays:A list dates that should be considered non-work days
FORMULA.YEARFRAC: Calculates the fraction of the year represented by the number of whole days between two dates (the start_date and the end_date). For instance, you can use YEARFRAC to identify the proportion of a whole year's benefits, or obligations to assign to a specific term.
FORMULA.YEARFRAC-OPT: start_date:A valid date in text format;end_date:A valid date in text format;basis:The type of day count basis to use
FORMULA.ACCRINT: Returns the accrued interest for a security that pays periodic interest.
FORMULA.ACCRINT-OPT: id:Issue date of the security;fd:First interest date of security;sd:Settlement date of security;rate:Interest rate of security;par :Par value of security;freq:Coupon payments per year (annual = 1, semiannual = 2; quarterly = 4);basis:Day count basis (default =0);calc:Calculation method (default = TRUE).
FORMULA.CUMIPMT: A financial function that returns the cumulative interest paid on a loan between a start period and an end period. You can use CUMIPMT to calculate and verify the total interest paid on a loan, or the interest paid between any two payment periods
FORMULA.CUMIPMT-OPT: rate:The interest rate per period;nper:The total number of payments for the loan;pv:The present value, or total value of all payments now;start_period:First payment in calculation;end_period:Last payment in calculation;type:When payments are due. 0 = end of period. 1 = beginning of period.
FORMULA.CUMPRINC: Is a financial function that returns the cumulative principal paid on a loan between a start period and an end period. You can use CUMPRINC to calculate and verify the total principal paid on a loan, or the principal paid between any two payment periods
FORMULA.CUMPRINC-OPT: rate:The interest rate per period;nper:The total number of payments for the loan;pv:The present value, or total value of all payments now;start_period:First payment in calculation;end_period:Last payment in calculation;type:When payments are due. 0 = end of period. 1 = beginning of period.
FORMULA.DB: Returns the depreciation of an asset for a specified period using the fixed-declining balance method. The calculation is based on initial asset cost, salvage value, the number of periods over which the asset is depreciated and, optionally, the number of months in the first year
FORMULA.DB-OPT: cost:Initial cost of asset;salvage:Asset value at the end of the depreciation;life:Periods over which asset is depreciated;period:Period to calculation depreciation for;month:Number of months in the first year. Defaults to 12
FORMULA.DDB: Returns the depreciation of an asset for a given period using the double-declining balance method or another method you specify by changing the factor argument
FORMULA.DDB-OPT: cost:Initial cost of asset;salvage:Asset value at the end of the depreciation;life:Periods over which asset is depreciated;period:Period to calculation depreciation for;factor:Rate at which the balance declines. If omitted, defaults to 2
FORMULA.DOLLARDE: Converts a dollar price entered with a special notation to a dollar price displayed as a decimal number
FORMULA.DOLLARDE-OPT: fractional_dollar:Dollar component in special fractional notation;fraction:The denominator in the fractional unit. 8 = 1/8, 16 = 1/16, 32 = 1/32, etc
FORMULA.DOLLARFR: Converts a dollar price in a regular decimal number format to a dollar price in a particular fractional notation used for securities where pricing is given to the nearest 1/8, 1/16, 1/32, etc
FORMULA.DOLLARFR-OPT: decimal_dollar:Pricing as a normal decimal number;fraction:The denominator in the fractional unit. 8 = 1/8, 16 = 1/16, 32 = 1/32, etc.
FORMULA.EFFECT: Returns the effective annual interest rate, given a nominal interest rate and the number of compounding periods per year. Effective annual interest rate is the interest rate actually earned due to compounding
FORMULA.EFFECT-OPT: nominal_rate:The nominal or stated interest rate;npery:Number of compounding periods per year
FORMULA.FV: Is a financial function that returns the future value of an investment. You can use the FV function to get the future value of an investment assuming periodic, constant payments with a constant interest rate
FORMULA.FV-OPT: rate:The interest rate per period;nper:The total number of payment periods;pmt:The payment made each period. Must be entered as a negative number;pv:The present value of future payments. If omitted, assumed to be zero. Must be entered as a negative number;type:When payments are due. 0 = end of period, 1 = beginning of period. Default is 0
FORMULA.FVSCHEDULE: Returns the future value of a single sum based on a schedule of given interest rates. FVSCHEDULE can be used to find the future value of an investment with a variable or adjustable rate.
FORMULA.FVSCHEDULE-OPT: principal:The initial investment sum;schedule:Schedule of interest rates, provided as range or array
FORMULA.IPMT: Can be used to calculate the interest portion of a given loan payment in a given payment period. For example, you can use IPMT to get the interest amount of a payment for the first period, the last period, or any period in between.
FORMULA.IPMT-OPT: rate:The interest rate per period;per:The payment period of interest;nper:The total number of payment periods;pv:The present value, or total value of all payments now;fv:The cash balance desired after last payment is made. Defaults to 0;type:When payments are due. 0 = end of period. 1 = beginning of period. Default is 0
FORMULA.IRR: Is a financial function that returns the internal rate of return (IRR) for a series of cash flows that occur at regular intervals.
FORMULA.IRR-OPT: values:Array or reference to cells that contain values;guess:An estimate for expected IRR. Default is .1 (10%)
FORMULA.ISPMT: Calculates the interest paid during a given period of an investment where principal payments are equal. The given period is specified as a zero-based number instead of a 1-based number.
FORMULA.ISPMT-OPT: rate:Interest rate;per:Period (starts with zero, not 1);nper:Number of periods;pv:Present value
FORMULA.MIRR: Is a financial function that returns the modified internal rate of return (MIRR) for a series of cash flows, taking into account both discount rate and reinvestment rate for future cash flows
FORMULA.MIRR-OPT: values:Array or reference to cells that contain cash flows;finance_rate:Required rate of return (discount rate) as percentage;reinvest_rate:Interest rate received on cash flows reinvested as percentage
FORMULA.NOMINAL: Returns the nominal interest rate, given an effective annual interest rate and the number of compounding periods per year. The effective rate is the actual rate due to compounding. The nominal rate is typically the stated rate
FORMULA.NOMINAL-OPT: effect_rate:The effective annual interest rate;npery:Number of compounding periods per year
FORMULA.NPER: Is a financial function that returns the number of periods for loan or investment. You can use the NPER function to get the number of payment periods for a loan, given the amount, the interest rate, and periodic payment amount
FORMULA.NPER-OPT: rate:The interest rate per period;pmt:The payment made each period;pv:The present value, or total value of all payments now;fv:The future value, or a cash balance you want after the last payment is made. Defaults to 0;type:When payments are due. 0 = end of period. 1 = beginning of period. Default is 0
FORMULA.NPV: Is a financial function that calculates the net present value (NPV) of an investment using a discount rate and a series of future cash flows
FORMULA.NPV-OPT: rate:Discount rate over one period;value1:First value(s) representing cash flows;value2:Second value(s) representing cash flows
FORMULA.PDURATION: Returns the number of periods required for an investment to reach a desired value.
FORMULA.PDURATION-OPT: rate:Interest rate per period;pv:Present value of the investment;fv:Future value of the investment
FORMULA.PMT: Is a financial function that returns the periodic payment for a loan. You can use the PMT function to figure out payments for a loan, given the loan amount, number of periods, and interest rate
FORMULA.PMT-OPT: rate:The interest rate for the loan;nper:The total number of payments for the loan;pv:The present value, or total value of all loan payments now;fv:The future value, or a cash balance you want after the last payment is made. Defaults to 0 (zero);type:When payments are due. 0 = end of period. 1 = beginning of period. Default is 0
FORMULA.PPMT: Can be used to calculate the principal portion of a given loan payment. For example, you can use PPMT to get the principal amount of a payment for the first period, the last period, or any period in between.
FORMULA.PPMT-OPT: rate:The interest rate per period;per:The payment period of interest;nper:The total number of payment periods;pv:The present value, or total value of all payments now;fv:The cash balance desired after last payment is made. Defaults to 0;type:When payments are due. 0 = end of period. 1 = beginning of period. Default is 0
FORMULA.PV: Is a financial function that returns the present value of an investment. You can use the PV function to get the value in today's dollars of a series of future payments, assuming periodic, constant payments and a constant interest rate.
FORMULA.PV-OPT: rate:The interest rate per period;nper:The total number of payment periods;pmt:The payment made each period;fv:A cash balance you want to attain after the last payment is made. If omitted, assumed to be zero;type:When payments are due. 0 = end of period, 1 = beginning of period. Default is 0
FORMULA.RATE: Is a financial function that returns the interest rate per period of an annuity. You can use RATE to calculate the periodic interest rate, then multiply as required to derive the annual interest rate. The RATE function calculates by iteration.
FORMULA.RATE-OPT: nper:The total number of payment periods;pmt:The payment made each period;pv:The present value, or total value of all loan payments now;fv:The future value, or desired cash balance after last payment. Default is 0;type:When payments are due. 0 = end of period. 1 = beginning of period. Default is 0;guess:Your guess on the rate. Default is 10%
FORMULA.BIN2DEC: Converts a binary number to the decimal equivalent. The input number must contain only zeros and ones and be less than 10 characters long, otherwise the function returns the #NUM! error value.
FORMULA.BIN2DEC-OPT: number:The binary number you want to convert to decimal
FORMULA.BIN2HEX: Converts a binary number to its hexadecimal equivalent.
FORMULA.BIN2HEX-OPT: number:The binary number you want to convert to hexadecimal;places:If omitted uses the least number of characters required to represent the number, otherwise pads the result with zeros up to the specified number of places
FORMULA.BIN2OCT: Converts a binary number to its octal equivalent.
FORMULA.BIN2OCT-OPT: number:The binary number you want to convert to octal;places:If omitted uses the least number of characters required to represent the number, otherwise pads the result with zeros up to the specified number of places
FORMULA.BITAND: Returns a decimal number representing the bitwise AND of two numbers.
FORMULA.BITAND-OPT: number1:A positive decimal number;number2:A positive decimal number
FORMULA.BITLSHIFT: Shifts a number by the specified number of bits, effectively doubling or halving the number a specified number of times.
FORMULA.BITLSHIFT-OPT: number:The number to be bit shifted;shift_amount:The amount of bits to shift, if negative shifts bits to the right instead
FORMULA.BITOR: Returns a decimal number representing the bitwise OR of two numbers. For each corresponding bit in the binary representation of the numbers a logical OR operation is performed, and the resulting number returned.
FORMULA.BITOR-OPT: number1:A positive decimal number;number2:A positive decimal number
FORMULA.BITRSHIFT: Shifts a number by the specified number of bits, effectively halving or doubling the number a specified number of times.
FORMULA.BITRSHIFT-OPT: number:The number to be bit shifted;shift_amount:The amount of bits to shift, if negative shifts bits to the right instead
FORMULA.BITXOR: Returns a decimal number representing the bitwise XOR of two numbers. For each corresponding bit in the binary representation of the numbers a logical XOR operation is performed and the resulting number returned.
FORMULA.BITXOR-OPT: number1:A positive decimal number;number2:A positive decimal number
FORMULA.COMPLEX: Creates a complex number with given real and imaginary coefficients. COMPLEX returns a text result in the form x + yi or x + yj.
FORMULA.COMPLEX-OPT: real_num:The real number;i_num:The imaginary number:suffix:The suffix, either "i" or "j"
FORMULA.CONVERT: Converts a number in one measurement system to another. For example, you can use CONVERT to convert feet into meters, pounds into kilograms, Fahrenheit to Celsius, gallons into liters, and for many other unit conversions.
FORMULA.CONVERT-OPT: number:The numeric value to convert;from_unit:The starting units for number;to_unit:The ending units for the result
FORMULA.DEC2BIN: Converts a decimal number to its binary equivalent.
FORMULA.DEC2BIN-OPT: number:The decimal number you want to convert to binary;places:Pads the resulting binary number with zeros up to the specified number of digits. If omitted returns the least number of characters required to represent the number
FORMULA.DEC2HEX: Converts a decimal number to its hexadecimal equivalent.
FORMULA.DEC2HEX-OPT: number:The decimal number you want to convert to hexadecimal;places:Pads the resulting binary number with zeros up to the specified number of digits. If omitted returns the least number of characters required to represent the number
FORMULA.DEC2OCT: Converts a decimal number to its octal equivalent
FORMULA.DEC2OCT-OPT: number:The decimal number you want to convert to octal;places:Pads the resulting binary number with zeros up to the specified number of digits. If omitted returns the least number of characters required to represent the number
FORMULA.DELTA: Will test if two numeric values are equal. When values are equal, DELTA returns 1, otherwise, DELTA returns zero.
FORMULA.ERF: Returns the error function integrated between lower_limit and upper_limit.
FORMULA.ERF-OPT: lower_limit:The lower bound for integrating ERF;upper_limit:The upper bound for integrating ERF. If omitted, ERF integrates between zero and lower_limit
FORMULA.ERFC: Returns the complementary ERF function integrated between x and infinity.
FORMULA.ERFC-OPT: number:The lower bound for integrating ERFC
FORMULA.GESTEP: Returns 1 if number ≥ step; returns 0 (zero) otherwise. Use this function to filter a set of values. For example, by summing several GESTEP functions you calculate the count of values that exceed a threshold.
FORMULA.GESTEP-OPT: number:The value to test against step;step:The threshold value. If you omit a value for step, GESTEP uses zero
FORMULA.HEX2BIN: Converts a hexadecimal number to its binary equivalent
FORMULA.HEX2BIN-OPT: number:The hexadecimal number you want to convert to binary;places:Pads the resulting binary number with zeros up to the specified number of digits. If omitted returns the least number of characters required to represent the number
FORMULA.HEX2DEC: Converts a hexadecimal number to its decimal equivalent
FORMULA.HEX2DEC-OPT: number:The hexadecimal number you want to convert to decimal;places:Pads the resulting binary number with zeros up to the specified number of digits. If omitted returns the least number of characters required to represent the number
FORMULA.HEX2OCT: Converts a hexadecimal number to its octal equivalent
FORMULA.HEX2OCT-OPT: number:The hexadecimal number you want to convert to octal;places:Pads the resulting octal number with zeros up to the specified number of digits. If omitted returns the least number of characters required to represent the number
FORMULA.IMABS: Returns the absolute value of a complex number in the form x + yi or x + yj. Use the COMPLEX function to create a complex number from real and imaginary parts.
FORMULA.IMAGINARY: Returns the imaginary coefficient of a complex number given in the form x + yi or x + yj.
FORMULA.IMARGUMENT: Returns the argument Theta (theta), an angle expressed in radians
FORMULA.IMCONJUGATE: Returns the complex conjugate of a complex number in x + yi or x + yj text format.
FORMULA.IMCOS: Returns the cosine of a complex number in x + yi or x + yj text format.
FORMULA.IMCOSH: Returns the hyperbolic cosine of a complex number in x+yi or x+yj text format.
FORMULA.IMCOT: Returns the cotangent of a complex number in x+yi or x+yj text format.
FORMULA.IMCSCH: Returns the hyperbolic cosecant of a complex number in x+yi or x+yj text format.
FORMULA.IMDIV: Returns the quotient of two complex numbers in x + yi or x + yj text format.
FORMULA.IMDIV-OPT: inumber1:The complex numerator or dividend;inumber2:The complex denominator or divisor
FORMULA.IMEXP: Returns the exponential of a complex number in x + yi or x + yj text format.
FORMULA.IMLN: Returns the natural logarithm of a complex number in x + yi or x + yj text format.
FORMULA.IMLOG10: Returns the common logarithm (base 10) of a complex number in x + yi or x + yj text format.
FORMULA.IMLOG2: Returns the base-2 logarithm of a complex number in x + yi or x + yj text format.
FORMULA.IMPOWER: Returns a complex number in x + yi or x + yj text format raised to a power.
FORMULA.IMPOWER-OPT: inumber:A complex number you want to raise to a power;number:The power to which you want to raise the complex number
FORMULA.IMPRODUCT: Returns the product of 1 to 255 complex numbers in x + yi or x + yj text format.
FORMULA.IMREAL: Returns the real coefficient of a complex number in x + yi or x + yj text format.
FORMULA.IMSEC: Returns the secant of a complex number in x+yi or x+yj text format.
FORMULA.IMSECH: Returns the hyperbolic secant of a complex number in x+yi or x+yj text format.
FORMULA.IMSIN: Returns the sine of a complex number in x + yi or x + yj text format.
FORMULA.IMSINH: Returns the hyperbolic sine of a complex number in x+yi or x+yj text format.
FORMULA.IMSQRT: Returns the square root of a complex number in x + yi or x + yj text format.
FORMULA.IMSUB: Returns the difference of two complex numbers in x + yi or x + yj text format.
FORMULA.IMSUB-OPT: inumber1:The complex number from which to subtract;inumber2:The complex number to subtract from inumber1
FORMULA.IMSUM: Returns the sum of two or more complex numbers in x + yi or x + yj text format.
FORMULA.IMSUM-OPT: inumber1:A complex number to add;inumber2:A complex number to add;inumber3:A complex number to add
FORMULA.IMTAN: Returns the tangent of a complex number in x+yi or x+yj text format.
FORMULA.OCT2BIN: Converts an octal number to binary.
FORMULA.OCT2BIN-OPT: number:The octal number you want to convert to binary;places:The number of characters to use. If places is omitted, OCT2BIN uses the minimum number of characters necessary. Places is useful for padding the return value with leading 0s (zeros).
FORMULA.OCT2DEC: Converts an octal number to decimal.
FORMULA.OCT2DEC-OPT: number:The octal number you want to convert. Number may not contain more than 10 octal characters (30 bits). The most significant bit of number is the sign bit. The remaining 29 bits are magnitude bits. Negative numbers are represented using two's-complement notation
FORMULA.OCT2HEX: Converts an octal number to hexadecimal.
FORMULA.OCT2HEX-OPT: number:The octal number you want to convert to hexa;places:The number of characters to use. If places is omitted, OCT2HEX uses the minimum number of characters necessary. Places is useful for padding the return value with leading 0s (zeros)
FORMULA.AND: Is a logical function used to require more than one condition at the same time. AND returns either TRUE or FALSE. To test if a number in A1 is greater than zero and less than 10, use =AND(A1>0,A1<10). The AND function can be used as the logical test inside the IF function to avoid extra nested IFs, and can be combined with the OR function. The AND function is used to check more than one logical condition at the same time, up to 255 conditions
FORMULA.AND-OPT: logical1:The first condition or logical value to evaluate;logical2:The second condition or logical value to evaluate
FORMULA.IF: Runs a logical test and returns one value for a TRUE result, and another for a FALSE result. For example, to "pass" scores above 70: =IF(A1>70,"Pass","Fail"). More than one condition can be tested by nesting IF functions. The IF function can be combined with logical functions like AND and OR to extend the logical test.
FORMULA.IF-OPT: logical_test:A value or logical expression that can be evaluated as TRUE or FALSE;value_if_true:The value to return when logical_test evaluates to TRUE;value_if_false:The value to return when logical_test evaluates to FALSE
FORMULA.IFS: Runs multiple tests and returns a value corresponding to the first TRUE result. Use the IFS function to evaluate multiple conditions without multiple nested IF statements. IFS allows shorter, easier to read formulas. Syntax: =IFS (test1, value1, [test2, value2], ...)
FORMULA.IFS-OPT: test1:first logical test;value1:Result when test1 is true
FORMULA.IFERROR: Returns a custom result when a formula generates an error, and a standard result when no error is detected. IFERROR is an elegant way to trap and manage errors without using more complicated nested IF statements.
FORMULA.IFERROR-OPT: value:The value, reference, or formula to check for an error;value_if_error:The value to return if an error is found
FORMULA.IFNA: Returns a custom result when a formula generates the #N/A error, and a standard result when no error is detected. IFNA is an elegant way to trap and handle #N/A errors specifically without catching other errors.
FORMULA.IFNA-OPT: value:The value, reference, or formula to check for an error;value_if_na:The value to return if #N/A error is found
FORMULA.NOT: Returns the opposite of a given logical or boolean value. When given TRUE, NOT returns FALSE.When given FALSE, NOT returns TRUE. Use the NOT function to reverse a logical value.
FORMULA.NOT-OPT: logical:A value or logical expression that can be evaluated as TRUE or FALSE.
FORMULA.OR: Is a logical function to test multiple conditions at the same time. OR returns either TRUE or FALSE. For example, to test A1 for either "x" or "y", use =OR(A1="x",A1="y"). The OR function can be used as the logical test inside the IF function to avoid extra nested IFs, and can be combined with the AND function. Syntax: =OR (logical1, [logical2], ...)
FORMULA.OR-OPT: logical1:The first condition or logical value to evaluate;logical2:The second condition or logical value to evaluate
FORMULA.SWITCH: Compares one value against a list of values, and returns a result corresponding to the first match. SWITCH can return an optional default value when no match is found. Syntax: =SWITCH (expression, val1/result1, [val2/result2], ..., [default])
FORMULA.SWITCH-OPT: expression:The value or expression to match against;val1_result1:The first value and result pair;val2/result2:The second value and result pair;default:The default value to use when no match is found
FORMULA.TRUE: Returns the value TRUE. TRUE is classified as a compatibility function, and not needed in most cases. It is equivalent to using the Boolean value TRUE directly in a formula.
FORMULA.XOR: Performs what is called "exclusive OR". With two logical statements, XOR returns TRUE if either statement is TRUE, but returns FALSE if both statements are TRUE. If neither is TRUE, XOR also returns FALSE. Syntax: =XOR (logical1, [logical2], ...)
FORMULA.XOR-OPT: logical1:An expression, constant, or reference that evaluates to TRUE or FALSE;logical2:An expression, constant, or reference that evaluates to TRUE or FALSE
FORMULA.ABS: Returns the absolute value of a number. Negative numbers are converted to positive numbers, and positive numbers are unaffected.
FORMULA.ABS-OPT: number:The number to get the absolute value of
FORMULA.ACOS: Returns the inverse cosine of a number. The function is the inverse of COS and expects input in the range from -1 to 1.
FORMULA.ACOS-OPT: number:The value to get the inverse cosine of. The number must be between -1 and 1 inclusive
FORMULA.ACOSH: Returns the inverse hyperbolic cosine of a number. The number must be greater than or equal to 1. The inverse hyperbolic cosine is the value whose hyperbolic cosine is number, so ACOSH(COSH(number)) equals number.
FORMULA.ACOSH-OPT: number:Any real number equal to or greater than 1
FORMULA.ACOT: Returns the principal value of the arccotangent, or inverse cotangent, of a number.
FORMULA.ACOT-OPT: number:Number is the cotangent of the angle you want. This must be a real number
FORMULA.ACOTH: Returns the inverse hyperbolic cotangent of a number.
FORMULA.ACOTH-OPT: number:The absolute value of Number must be greater than 1
FORMULA.AGGREGATE: Returns a aggregate calculation like AVERAGE, COUNT, MAX, etc., optionally ignoring hidden rows and errors. A total of 19 operations are available, specified by function number in the first argument
FORMULA.AGGREGATE-OPT: function_num:Operation to perform (1-19);options:Values to ignore (0-7);ref1:First argument;ref2:Second argument (k)
FORMULA.ARABIC: Converts a Roman numeral, as text, to a number in Arabic numeral. For example, the formula =ARABIC("VII") returns 7
FORMULA.ARABIC-OPT: roman_text:The Roman numeral in text that you want to convert
FORMULA.ASIN: Returns the inverse sine of a number.
FORMULA.ASIN-OPT: number:The value to get the inverse sine of. The number must be between -1 and 1 inclusive
FORMULA.ASINH: Returns the inverse hyperbolic sine of a number. The inverse hyperbolic sine is the value whose hyperbolic sine is number, so ASINH(SINH(number)) equals number.
FORMULA.ATAN: Returns the inverse tangent of a number. The function is the inverse of TAN.
FORMULA.ATAN-OPT: number:The value to get the inverse tangent of
FORMULA.ATAN2: Returns the arctangent from x- and y-coordinates. In geometric terms, the function returns the radian angle corresponding to the input point.
FORMULA.ATAN2-OPT: x_num:The x coordinate of the input point;y_num:The y coordinate of the input point
FORMULA.ATANH: Returns the inverse hyperbolic tangent of a number. Number must be between -1 and 1 (excluding -1 and 1). The inverse hyperbolic tangent is the value whose hyperbolic tangent is number, so ATANH(TANH(number)) equals number.
FORMULA.BASE-OPT: number:The number you want to convert to another representation;radix:The base of the representation being converted to;min_length:Guarantees the minimum length of the returned string by padding the string with zeros
FORMULA.CEILING: Rounds a given number up to the nearest specified multiple. CEILING works like the MROUND function, but CEILING always rounds up.
FORMULA.CEILING-OPT: number:The number that should be rounded;significance:The multiple to use when rounding
FORMULA.CEILINGMATH: Rounds a number up to a specified multiple. Unlike the CEILING function, CEILING.MATH defaults to a multiple of 1, and provides explicit control over rounding direction for negative numbers.
FORMULA.CEILINGMATH-OPT: number:The number that should be rounded;significance:Multiple to use when rounding. Default is 1;mode:For rounding negative numbers toward or away from zero. Default is 0
FORMULA.CEILINGPRECISE: Rounds a number up to a given multiple. Unlike the CEILING function, CEILING.MATH defaults to a multiple of 1, and always rounds negative numbers toward zero.
FORMULA.CEILINGPRECISE-OPT: number:The number that should be rounded;significance:Multiple to use when rounding. Default is 1
FORMULA.COMBIN: Returns the number of combinations for a given number of items. The COMBIN function does not allow repetitions. To count combinations that allow repetitions, use the COMBINA function.
FORMULA.COMBIN-OPT: number:The total number of items;number_chosen:The number of items in each combination
FORMULA.COMBINA: Returns the number of combinations with repetitions allowed. To count combinations that do not allow repetitions, use the COMBIN function.
FORMULA.COMBINA-OPT: number:The total number of items;number_chosen:The number of items in each combination
FORMULA.COS: Returns the cosine of an angle given in radians. To supply an angle to COS in degrees, use the RADIANS function to convert to radians.
FORMULA.COS-OPT: number:The angle in radians for which you want the cosine
FORMULA.COSH: Returns the hyperbolic cosine of a number.
FORMULA.COT: Returns the cotangent of an angle provided in radians.
FORMULA.COTH: Return the hyperbolic cotangent of a hyperbolic angle.
FORMULA.CSC: Returns the cosecant of an angle provided in radians.
FORMULA.CSCH: Return the hyperbolic cosecant of an angle specified in radians.
FORMULA.DECIMAL: Converts an alpha-numeric number into its decimal equivalent.
FORMULA.DECIMAL-OPT: number:A string of alpha-numeric characters;radix:A number within the range [2, 36] that represents the base of the number to be converted
FORMULA.EVEN: Returns the next even integer after rounding a given number up. The EVEN function always rounds numbers up (away from zero) so positive numbers become larger and negative numbers become smaller (i.e. more negative).
FORMULA.EVEN-OPT: number:The number to round up to an even integer
FORMULA.EXP: Returns the result of the constant e raised to the power of a number. The constant e is a numeric constant relating to exponential growth and decay whose value is approximately 2.71828. The EXP function is the inverse of the LN (natural logarithm) function.
FORMULA.EXP-OPT: number:The power that e is raised to
FORMULA.FACT: Returns the factorial of a given number. For example, =FACT(3) returns 6, equivalent to 3 x 2 x 1.
FORMULA.FACT-OPT: number:The number to get the factorial of
FORMULA.FACTDOUBLE: Returns the double factorial of a number. A double factorial is symbolized by two exclamation marks (!!).
FORMULA.FACTDOUBLE-OPT: number:A number greater than or equal to -1
FORMULA.FLOOR: Rounds a given number down to the nearest specified multiple. FLOOR works like the MROUND function, but FLOOR always rounds down.
FORMULA.FLOOR-OPT: number:The number that should be rounded;significance:The multiple to use when rounding
FORMULA.FLOORMATH: Rounds a number down to a specified multiple. Unlike the FLOOR function, FLOOR.MATH defaults to a multiple of 1, and provides explicit support for rounding negative numbers.
FORMULA.FLOORMATH-OPT: number:The number that should be rounded;significance:The multiple to use when rounding;mode:For rounding negative numbers toward or away from zero. Default is 0
FORMULA.FLOORPRECISE: Rounds a number down to a specified multiple. Unlike the FLOOR function, FLOOR.PRECISE defaults to a multiple of 1, and always rounds negative numbers away from zero.
FORMULA.FLOORPRECISE-OPT: number:The number that should be rounded;significance:The multiple to use when rounding
FORMULA.GCD: Returns the greatest common divisor of two or more integers. The greatest common divisor is the largest integer that goes into all supplied numbers without a remainder. For example, =GCD(60,36) returns 12.
FORMULA.INT: Returns the integer part of a decimal number by rounding down to the integer. Note the INT function rounds down, so negative numbers become more negative. For example, while INT(10.8) returns 10, INT(-10.8) returns -11.
FORMULA.INT-OPT: number:The number from which you want an integer
FORMULA.ISEVEN: Returns TRUE when a numeric value is even, and FALSE for odd numbers. ISEVEN will return the #VALUE error when a value is not numeric.
FORMULA.ISOCEILING: Returns a number that is rounded up to the nearest integer or to the nearest multiple of significance. Regardless of the sign of the number, the number is rounded up. However, if the number or the significance is zero, zero is returned.
FORMULA.ISOCEILING-OPT: number:The number that should be rounded;significance:The multiple to use when rounding
FORMULA.ISODD: Returns TRUE when a numeric value is odd, and FALSE for even numbers. ISODD will return the #VALUE error when a value is not numeric.
FORMULA.LCM: Returns the least common multiple of integers. The least common multiple is the smallest positive integer that is a multiple of all supplied numbers. For example, =LCM(25,40) returns 200.
FORMULA.LN: Returns the natural logarithm of a given number.
FORMULA.LN-OPT: number:A number to take the natural logarithm of
FORMULA.LOG: Returns the logarithm of a given number, using a supplied base. The base argument defaults to 10 if not supplied.
FORMULA.LOG-OPT: number:Number for which you want the logarithm;base:Base of the logarithm. Defaults to 10
FORMULA.LOG10: Returns the base 10 logarithm of a number. For example, LOG10(100) returns 2, and LOG10(1000) returns 3.
FORMULA.LOG10-OPT: number:Number for which you want the logarithm
FORMULA.MOD: Returns the remainder of two numbers after division.  For example, MOD(10,3) = 1. The result of MOD carries the same sign as the divisor.
FORMULA.MOD-OPT: number:The number to be divided;divisor:The number to divide with
FORMULA.MROUND: Returns a number rounded to a given multiple. MROUND will round a number up or down, depending on the nearest multiple.
FORMULA.MROUND-OPT: number:The number that should be rounded;significance:The multiple to use when rounding
FORMULA.MULTINOMIAL: Returns the ratio of the factorial of a sum of values to the product of factorials. Number1 is required, subsequent numbers are optional. 1 to 255 values for which you want the multinomial.
FORMULA.ODD: Round a number up to the next odd integer.
FORMULA.ODD-OPT: number:The number to round up to an odd integer
FORMULA.POWER: Returns a number to a given power. The POWER function works like an exponent in a standard math equation.
FORMULA.POWER-OPT: number:Number to raise to a power;power:Power to raise number to (the exponent)
FORMULA.PRODUCT: Returns the product of numbers provided as arguments. The PRODUCT function is helpful when when multiplying many cells together. The formula =PRODUCT(A1:A3) is the same as =A1*A2*A3.
FORMULA.PRODUCT-OPT: number1:The first number or range to multiply;number2:The second number or range to multiply
FORMULA.QUOTIENT: Returns the result of integer division without the remainder.
FORMULA.QUOTIENT-OPT: numerator:The quantity to be divided;denominator:The divisor
FORMULA.RADIANS: Converts degrees to radians. For example, =RADIANS(180) returns 3.1415 or the value of π (pi).
FORMULA.RADIANS-OPT: angle:Angle in degrees to convert to radians
FORMULA.RAND: Returns a random number between 0 and 1. For example, =RAND() will generate a number like 0.422245717. RAND recalculates when a worksheet is opened or changed
FORMULA.RANDBETWEEN: Returns a random integer between given numbers. RANDBETWEEN recalculates when a worksheet is opened or changed.
FORMULA.RANDBETWEEN-OPT: bottom:An integer representing the lower value of the range;top:An integer representing the upper value of the range
FORMULA.ROUND: Returns a number rounded to a given number of digits. The ROUND function can round to the right or left of the decimal point.
FORMULA.ROUND-OPT: number:The number to round;num_digits:The number of digits to which number should be rounded
FORMULA.ROUNDDOWN: Returns a number rounded down to a given number of places. Unlike standard rounding, where only numbers less than 5 are rounded down, ROUNDDOWN rounds all numbers down.
FORMULA.ROUNDDOWN-OPT: number:The number to round;num_digits:The number of digits to which number should be rounded
FORMULA.ROUNDUP: Returns a number rounded up to a given number of decimal places. Unlike standard rounding, where numbers less than 5 are rounded down, ROUNDUP rounds all numbers up.
FORMULA.ROUNDUP-OPT: number:The number to round;num_digits:The number of digits to which number should be rounded
FORMULA.SEC: Returns the secant of an angle provided in radians.
FORMULA.SEC-OPT: number:The angle in radians for which you want the secant
FORMULA.SECH: Returns the hyperbolic secant of an angle.
FORMULA.SECH-OPT: number:It is the angle expressed in radians whose hyperbolic secant you want to obtain
FORMULA.SIGN: Returns the sign of a number as +1, -1 or 0. If number is positive, SIGN returns 1. If number is negative, sign returns -1. If number is zero, SIGN returns 0.
FORMULA.SIGN-OPT: number:The number to get the sign of
FORMULA.SIN: Returns the sine of angle given in radians. To supply an angle to SIN in degrees, multiply the angle by PI()/180 or use the RADIANS function to convert to radians.
FORMULA.SIN-OPT: number:The angle in radians for which you want the sine
FORMULA.SINH: Returns the hyperbolic sine of a number.
FORMULA.SQRT: Returns the square root of a positive number. SQRT returns an error if number is negative.
FORMULA.SQRT-OPT: number:The number to get the square root of
FORMULA.SQRTPI: Returns the square root of (number * pi).
FORMULA.SQRTPI-OPT: number:The number by which pi is multiplied
FORMULA.SUBTOTAL: Returns an aggregate result for supplied values. SUBTOTAL can return a SUM, AVERAGE, COUNT, MAX, and others (see table below), and SUBTOTAL function can either include or exclude values in hidden rows.
FORMULA.SUBTOTAL-OPT: function_num:A number that specifies which function to use in calculating subtotals within a list. (See table);ref1:A named range or reference to subtotal;ref2:A named range or reference to subtotal
FORMULA.SUM: Returns the sum of values supplied. These values can be numbers, cell references, ranges, arrays, and constants, in any combination. SUM can handle up to 255 individual arguments.
FORMULA.SUM-OPT: number1:The first value to sum;number2:The second value to sum;number3:The third value to sum
FORMULA.SUMIF: Returns the sum of cells that meet a single condition. Criteria can be applied to dates, numbers, and text. The SUMIF function supports logical operators (>,<,<>,=) and wildcards (*,?) for partial matching.
FORMULA.SUMIF-OPT: range:The range of cells that you want to apply the criteria against;criteria:The criteria used to determine which cells to add;sum_range:The cells to add together. If sum_range is omitted, the cells in range are added together instead
FORMULA.SUMIFS: Is a function to sum cells that meet multiple criteria. SUMIFS can be used to sum values when adjacent cells meet criteria based on dates, numbers, and text. SUMIFS supports logical operators (>,<,<>,=) and wildcards (*,?) for partial matching.
FORMULA.SUMIFS-OPT: sum_range:The range to be summed;range1:The first range to evaulate;criteria1:The criteria to use on range1;range2:The second range to evaluate;criteria2:The criteria to use on range2
FORMULA.SUMPRODUCT: Multiplies ranges or arrays together and returns the sum of products. This sounds boring, but SUMPRODUCT is an incredibly versatile function that can be used to count and sum like COUNTIFS or SUMIFS, but with more flexibility. Other functions can easily be used inside SUMPRODUCT to extend functionality even further.
FORMULA.SUMPRODUCT-OPT: array1:The first array or range to multiply, then add;array2:The second array or range to multiply, then add
FORMULA.SUMSQ: Returns the sum of the squares of the values provided. Values can be supplied as constants, cell references, or ranges.
FORMULA.SUMSQ-OPT: number1:The first argument containing numeric values;number2:The first argument containing numeric values
FORMULA.SUMX2MY2: Returns the sum of the difference of squares of corresponding values in two arrays. Values can be supplied as constants, cell references, or ranges
FORMULA.SUMX2MY2-OPT: array_x:The first range or array containing numeric values;array_y:The second range or array containing numeric values.
FORMULA.SUMX2PY2: Returns the sum of the sum of squares of corresponding values in two arrays. Values can be supplied as constants, cell references, or ranges
FORMULA.SUMX2PY2-OPT: array_x:The first range or array containing numeric values;array_y:The second range or array containing numeric values.
FORMULA.SUMXMY2: Returns the sum of squares of differences between corresponding values in two arrays. Values can be supplied as constants, cell references, or ranges
FORMULA.SUMXMY2-OPT: array_x:The first range or array containing numeric values;array_y:The second range or array containing numeric values.
FORMULA.TAN: Returns the tangent of angle given in radians. To supply an angle to TAN in degrees, multiply the angle by PI()/180 or use the RADIANS function to convert to radians
FORMULA.TAN-OPT: number:The angle in radians for which you want the tangent
FORMULA.TANH: Returns the hyperbolic tangent of a number.
FORMULA.TRUNC: Returns a truncated number based on an (optional) number of digits. For example, TRUNC(4.9) will return 4, and TRUNC(-3.5) will return -3. The TRUNC function does no rounding, it simply truncates as specified
FORMULA.TRUNC-OPT: number:The number to truncate;num_digits:The precision of the truncation (default is 0)
FORMULA.AVEDEV: Returns the average of the absolute value of deviations from the mean for a given set of data. Average deviation is a measure of variability
FORMULA.AVEDEV-OPT: number1:First value or reference;number2:Second value or reference
FORMULA.AVERAGE: Calculates the average (arithmetic mean) of supplied numbers. AVERAGE can handle up to 255 individual arguments, which can include numbers, cell references, ranges, arrays, and constants
FORMULA.AVERAGE-OPT: number1:A number or cell reference that refers to numeric values;number2:A number or cell reference that refers to numeric values
FORMULA.AVERAGEA: Returns the average of a set of supplied values. Unlike AVERAGE, AVERAGEA will also evaluate the logical values TRUE and FALSE, and numbers represented as text, whereas AVERAGE ignores these values during calculation
FORMULA.AVERAGEA-OPT: value1:A value or reference to a value that can be evaluated as a number;value2:A value or reference to a value that can be evaluated as a number
FORMULA.AVERAGEIF: Calculates the average of numbers in a range that meet supplied criteria. AVERAGEIF criteria can include logical operators (>,<,<>,=) and wildcards (*,?) for partial matching
FORMULA.AVERAGEIF-OPT: range:One or more cells, including numbers or names, arrays, or references;criteria:A number, expression, cell reference, or text;average_range:The cells to average. When omitted, range is used
FORMULA.AVERAGEIFS: Calculates the average of numbers in a range that meet one or more criteria. The criteria used for AVERAGEIFS can include logical operators (>,<,<>,=) and wildcards (*,?) for partial matching
FORMULA.AVERAGEIFS-OPT: avg_rng:The range to average;range1:The first range to evaulate;criteria1:The criteria to use on range1;range2:The second range to evaluate;criteria2:The criteria to use on range2
FORMULA.BETADIST: Returns the cumulative beta probability density function. The beta distribution is commonly used to study variation in the percentage of something across samples, such as the fraction of the day people spend watching television
FORMULA.BETADIST-OPT: value:The value between A and B at which to evaluate the function;alpha:A parameter of the distribution;beta:A parameter of the distribution;lower:A lower bound to the interval of x;upper:An upper bound to the interval of x
FORMULA.BETAINV: Returns the inverse of the cumulative beta probability density function for a specified beta distribution. That is, if probability = BETADIST(x,...), then BETAINV(probability,...) = x. The beta distribution can be used in project planning to model probable completion times given an expected completion time and variability
FORMULA.BETAINV-OPT: prob:A probability associated with the beta distribution;alpha:A parameter of the distribution;beta:A parameter of the distribution;lower:A lower bound to the interval of x;upper:An upper bound to the interval of x
FORMULA.BINOMDIST: Returns the individual term binomial distribution probability. You can use BINOMDIST to calculate probabilities that an event will occur a certain number of times in a given number of trials
FORMULA.BINOMDIST-OPT: number_s:The number of successes;trials:The number of independent trials;probability_s:The probability of success on each trial;cumulative:TRUE = cumulative distribution function, FALSE=probability mass function
FORMULA.CORREL: Returns the correlation coefficient of two cell ranges. Use the correlation coefficient to determine the relationship between two properties. For example, you can examine the relationship between a location's average temperature and the use of air conditioners
FORMULA.CORREL-OPT: array1:A range of cell values;array2:A second range of cell values
FORMULA.COUNT: Returns a count of values that are numbers. Numbers include negative numbers, percentages, dates, times, fractions, and formulas that return numbers. Empty cells and text values are ignored.
FORMULA.COUNT-OPT: value1:An item, cell reference, or range;value2:An item, cell reference, or range
FORMULA.COUNTA: Returns the count of cells that contain numbers, text, logical values, error values, and empty text (""). COUNTA does not count empty cells
FORMULA.COUNTA-OPT: value1:An item, cell reference, or range;value2:An item, cell reference, or range
FORMULA.COUNTBLANK: Returns a count of empty cells in a range. Cells that contain text, numbers, errors, spaces, etc. are not counted. Formulas that return empty text are counted.
FORMULA.COUNTBLANK-OPT: range:The range in which to count blank cells
FORMULA.COUNTIF: Count cells in a range that meet a single condition. COUNTIF can be used to count cells that contain dates, numbers, and text. The criteria used in COUNTIF supports logical operators (>,<,<>,=) and wildcards (*,?) for partial matchingReturns a count of empty cells in a range. Cells that contain text, numbers, errors, spaces, etc. are not counted. Formulas that return empty text are counted.
FORMULA.COUNTIF-OPT: range:The range of cells to count;criteria:The criteria that controls which cells should be counted
FORMULA.COUNTIFS: Returns the count of cells that meet one or more criteria. COUNTIFS can be used with criteria based on dates, numbers, text, and other conditions. COUNTIFS supports logical operators (>,<,<>,=) and wildcards (*,?) for partial matching
FORMULA.COUNTIFS-OPT: range1:The first range to evaluate;criteria1:The criteria to use on range1;range2:The second range to evaluate;criteria2:The criteria to use on range2
FORMULA.COUNTUNIQUE: Counts the number of unique values in a list of specified values and ranges
FORMULA.COVARIANCEP: Returns the population covariance, the average of the products of the deviations for each pair of data points in two data sets. Use covariance to determine the relationships between two data sets. For example, you can investigate whether higher income corresponds to higher education levels
FORMULA.COVARIANCEP-OPT: matrix1:The first whole number cell range;matrix2:The second whole number cell range
FORMULA.COVARIANCES: Returns the sample covariance, the average of the products of deviations for each data point pair in two data sets
FORMULA.COVARIANCES-OPT: matrix1:The first whole number cell range;matrix2:The second whole number cell range
FORMULA.DEVSQ: Returns the sum of squares of deviations of data points from their sample mean.
FORMULA.DEVSQ-OPT: numbers:Number1 is required, subsequent numbers are optional. 1 to 255 arguments for which you want to calculate the sum of squared deviations. You can also use a single array or a reference to an array instead of arguments separated by commas
FORMULA.EXPONDIST: Returns the exponential distribution. Use EXPONDIST to model the time between events, such as how long an automated bank teller takes to deliver cash. For example, you can use EXPONDIST to determine the probability that the process takes at most 1 minute
FORMULA.EXPONDIST-OPT: x:The value of the function;lambda:The parameter value;cumulative:A logical value that indicates which form of the exponential function to provide. If cumulative is TRUE, EXPONDIST returns the cumulative distribution function; if FALSE, it returns the probability density function
FORMULA.FDIST: Returns the (right-tailed) F probability distribution (degree of diversity) for two data sets. You can use this function to determine whether two data sets have different degrees of diversity. For example, you can examine the test scores of men and women entering high school and determine if the variability in the females is different from that found in the males
FORMULA.FDIST-OPT: x:The value at which to evaluate the function;deg_freedom1:The numerator degrees of freedom;deg_freedom2:The denominator degrees of freedom
FORMULA.FINV: Returns the inverse of the (right-tailed) F probability distribution. If p = FDIST(x,...), then FINV(p,...) = x. The F distribution can be used in an F-test that compares the degree of variability in two data sets. For example, you can analyze income distributions in the United States and Canada to determine whether the two countries have a similar degree of income diversity.
FORMULA.FINV-OPT: probability:A probability associated with the F cumulative distribution;deg_freedom1:The numerator degrees of freedom;deg_freedom2:The denominator degrees of freedom
FORMULA.FISHER: Returns the Fisher transformation at x. This transformation produces a function that is normally distributed rather than skewed. Use this function to perform hypothesis testing on the correlation coefficient
FORMULA.FISHER-OPT: x:A numeric value for which you want the transformation
FORMULA.FISHERINV: Returns the inverse of the Fisher transformation. Use this transformation when analyzing correlations between ranges or arrays of data. If y = FISHER(x), then FISHERINV(y) = x.
FORMULA.FISHERINV-OPT: y:The value for which you want to perform the inverse of the transformation
FORMULA.FORECAST: Predicts a value based on existing values along a linear trend. FORECAST calculates future value predictions using linear regression, and can be used to predict numeric values like sales, inventory, expenses, measurements, etc
FORMULA.FORECAST-OPT: x:The x value data point to use to calculate a prediction;known_ys:The dependent array or range of data (y values);kown_xs:The independent array or range of data (x values)
FORMULA.FREQUENCY: Returns a frequency distribution, which is a list that shows the frequency of values at given intervals. FREQUENCY returns multiple values and must be entered as an array formula with control-shift-enter
FORMULA.FREQUENCY-OPT: data_array:An array of values for which you want to get frequencies;bins_array:An array of intervals ("bins") for grouping values
FORMULA.GAMMA: Returns the value of the gamma function
FORMULA.GAMMALN: Returns the natural logarithm of the gamma function, Γ (x).
FORMULA.GAMMALN-OPT: number:It is the value for which you want to calculate GAMMA.LN
FORMULA.GAUSS: Finds the probability that a member of a standard normal population belongs to the category between the mean and z standard deviations from the mean
Known_y:El conjunto de valores de y que: Returns the geometric mean for a set of numeric values. Geometric mean can be used to calculate average rate of return with variable rates
FORMULA.GEOMEAN-OPT: number1:First value or reference;number2:Second value or reference
FORMULA.GROWTH: Calculates predicted exponential growth by using existing data. GROWTH returns the y-values for a series of new x-values that you specify by using existing x-values and y-values. You can also use the GROWTH worksheet function to fit an exponential curve to existing x-values and y-values
FORMULA.GROWTH-OPT: Known_y:The set of y-values you already know in the relationship;Known_x:An optional set of x-values that you may already know in the relationship.New_x:Are new x-values for which you want GROWTH to return corresponding y-values;Const:A logical value specifying whether to force the constant b to equal 1
FORMULA.HARMEAN: Returns the harmonic mean of a data set. The harmonic mean is the reciprocal of the arithmetic mean of reciprocals
FORMULA.HARMEAN-OPT: Number1:arguments for which you want to calculate the mean;Number2:subsequent numbers are optional. 1 to 255 arguments for which you want to calculate the mean. You can also use a single array or a reference to an array instead of arguments separated by commas
FORMULA.HYPGEOMDIST: Returns the value of the hypergeometric distribution for a given number of successes from a sample of a population.
FORMULA.HYPGEOMDIST-OPT: Sample_s:The number of successes in the sample;Number_sample:The size of the sample;Population_s:The number of successes in the population;Number_pop:The population size
FORMULA.INTERCEPT: Returns the point at which a regression line will intersect the y-axis based on known x and y values
FORMULA.INTERCEPT-OPT: known_ys:An array or range of numeric data points (dependent values);known_xs:An array or range of numeric data points (independent values)
FORMULA.KURT: Returns the kurtosis of a data set. Kurtosis characterizes the relative peakedness or flatness of a distribution compared with the normal distribution. Positive kurtosis indicates a relatively peaked distribution. Negative kurtosis indicates a relatively flat distribution
FORMULA.KURT-OPT: Number1:arguments for which you want to calculate the Kurt;Number2:subsequent numbers are optional. 1 to 255 arguments for which you want to calculate the kurt. You can also use a single array or a reference to an array instead of arguments separated by commas
FORMULA.LARGE: Returns a numeric value based on its position in a list when sorted by value in descending order. In other words, LARGE can retrieve the "nth largest" value – 1st largest value, 2nd largest value, 3rd largest value, etc
FORMULA.LARGE-OPT: array:An array or range of numeric values;k:Position as an integer, where 1 corresponds to the largest value
FORMULA.LINEST: Returns statistics for a best fit straight line through supplied x and y values. The values returned by LINEST include slope, intercept, standard error values, and more. To find the best fit of a line to the data, LINEST uses the "least squares" method
FORMULA.LINEST-OPT: known_ys:An array or range of dependent y values values;known_xs:An array or range of independent x values;const:Boolean - normal or force the constant b to equal 0. Default is TRUE = normal calculation;stats:Boolean - return additional statistics. Default is FALSE = slope and intercept only
FORMULA.LOGNORMDIST: Returns the cumulative lognormal distribution of x, where ln(x) is normally distributed with parameters mean and standard_dev. Use this function to analyze data that has been logarithmically transformed
FORMULA.LOGNORMDIST-OPT: X:The value at which to evaluate the function;Mean:The mean of ln(x);Standard_dev:The standard deviation of ln(x)
FORMULA.LOGNORMINV: Returns the inverse of the lognormal cumulative distribution function of x, where ln(x) is normally distributed with parameters Mean and Standard_dev. If p = LOGNORM.DIST(x,...) then LOGNORM.INV(p,...) = x
FORMULA.LOGNORMINV-OPT: X:The value at which to evaluate the function;Mean:The mean of ln(x);Standard_dev:The standard deviation of ln(x)
FORMULA.MAX: Returns the largest numeric value in the data provided. MAX ignores empty cells, the logical values TRUE and FALSE, and text values
FORMULA.MAX-OPT: number1:First value or reference;number2:Second value or reference
FORMULA.MAXA: Returns the largest numeric value in a range of values. The MAXA function ignores empty cells, but evaluates the logical values TRUE and FALSE as 1 and 0, and evaluates text as zero
FORMULA.MAXA-OPT: number1:First value or reference;number2:Second value or reference
FORMULA.MEDIAN: number1:First value or reference;number2:Second value or reference
FORMULA.MIN: Returns the smallest numeric value in the data provided. The MIN function ignores empty cells, the logical values TRUE and FALSE, and text values
FORMULA.MIN-OPT: number1:First value or reference;number2:Second value or reference
FORMULA.MINA: Returns the smallest numeric value in a range of values. The MINA function ignores empty cells, but evaluates the logical values TRUE and FALSE as 1 and 0, and evaluates text as zero when these values appear in a range or cell reference
FORMULA.MINA-OPT: number1:First value or reference;number2:Second value or reference
FORMULA.MODEMULT: Returns an array of the most frequently occurring numbers in a numeric data set. For example, =MODE.MULT(1,2,3,3,4,5,5) returns {3;5}, because there are two modes, 3 and 5
FORMULA.MODEMULT-OPT: number1:First value or reference;number2:Second value or reference
FORMULA.MODESNGL: Returns the most frequently occurring number in a numeric data set. For example, =MODE.SNGL(1,2,4,4,5,5,5,6) returns 5
FORMULA.MODESNGL-OPT: number1:First value or reference;number2:Second value or reference
FORMULA.NORMDIST: x:The input value x;mean:The center of the distribution:standard_dev:The standard deviation of the distribution;cumulative:A boolean value that determines whether the probability density function or the cumulative distribution function is used
FORMULA.NORMINV: Returns the inverse of the normal cumulative distribution for the specified mean and standard deviation. Given the probability of an event occurring below a threshold value, the function returns the threshold value associated with the probability
FORMULA.NORMINV-OPT: probability:The probability of an event occurring below a threshold;mean:The mean of the distribution;standard_dev:The standard deviation of the distribution
FORMULA.NORMSDIST: Returns output for the standard normal cumulative distribution (CDF) and the standard normal probability density function (PDF)
FORMULA.NORMSDIST-OPT: z:Numeric z-score value;cumulative:Logical value that determines the form of the function
FORMULA.NORMSINV: Returns the inverse of the standard normal cumulative distribution
FORMULA.NORMSINV-OPT: probability:A probability corresponding to the standard normal distribution
FORMULA.PEARSON: Returns the Pearson product moment correlation coefficient, r, a dimensionless index that ranges from -1.0 to 1.0 inclusive and reflects the extent of a linear relationship between two data sets
FORMULA.PEARSON-OPT: array1:A set of independent values;array2:A set of dependent values
FORMULA.PERCENTILEEXC: Calculates the "kth percentile" for a set of data where k is 0 to 1. A percentile is a value below which a given percentage of values in a data set fall. You can use PERCENTILE.EXC to determine the 90th percentile, the 80th percentile, etc
FORMULA.PERCENTILEEXC-OPT: array:Data values;k:A value between 0 and 1 that represents the k-th percentile
FORMULA.PERCENTILEINC: calculates the "kth percentile" for a set of data where k is 0 to 1, inclusive. A percentile is a value below which a given percentage of values in a data set fall. You can use PERCENTILE.INC to determine the 90th percentile, the 80th percentile, etc
FORMULA.PERCENTRANKEXC: Returns the relative rank of a value in a data set as a percentage representing how many values are less than or equal to the value. Percentile rank is commonly used as a way to interpret standing in standardized tests
FORMULA.PERCENTRANKEXC-OPT: array:Array of data values;x:Value to rank;significance:Number of significant digits in result. Defaults to 3
FORMULA.PERCENTRANKINC: Returns the relative rank of a value in a data set as a percentage representing the number of values less than or equal to the value. Percentile rank is commonly used as a way to interpret standing in standardized tests
FORMULA.PERCENTRANKINC-OPT: array:Array of data values;x:Value to rank;significance:Number of significant digits in result. Defaults to 3
FORMULA.PERMUT: Returns the number of permutations (combinations where order is significant) for a given number of items. The PERMUT function does not allow repetitions. To allow permutations with repetitions, use the PERMUTATIONA function
FORMULA.PERMUT-OPT: number:The total number of items;number_chosen:The number of items in each combination
FORMULA.PERMUTATIONA: Returns the number of permutations (combinations where order is significant) for a given number of items. The PERMUTATIONA function allows repetitions. To calculate the number of permutations without repetitions, use the PERMUT function
FORMULA.PERMUTATIONA-OPT: number:The total number of items;number_chosen:The number of items in each combination
FORMULA.PHI: Returns the value of the density function for a standard normal distribution.
FORMULA.PHI-OPT: X:X is the number for which you want the density of the standard normal distribution
FORMULA.POISSONDIST: Returns the Poisson distribution. A common application of the Poisson distribution is predicting the number of events over a specific time, such as the number of cars arriving at a toll plaza in 1 minute
FORMULA.POISSONDIST-OPT: x:The number of events;Mean:The expected numeric value;cumulative    :A logical value that determines the form of the probability distribution returned. If cumulative is TRUE, POISSON.DIST returns the cumulative Poisson probability that the number of random events occurring will be between zero and x inclusive. if FALSE, it returns the Poisson probability mass function that the number of events occurring will be exactly x.
FORMULA.PROB: Returns the probability that values in a range are between two limits. If upper_limit is not supplied, returns the probability that values in x_range are equal to lower_limit
FORMULA.PROB-OPT: x_range:The range of numeric values of x with which there are associated probabilities;prob_range:A set of probabilities associated with values in x_range;lower_limit:The lower bound on the value for which you want a probability;upper_limit:The optional upper bound on the value for which you want a probability
FORMULA.QUARTILEEXC: Returns the quartile for a given set of data. QUARTILE.EXC can return, first quartile, second quartile, and third quartile
FORMULA.QUARTILEEXC-OPT: array:A reference containing data to analyze;quart:The quartile value to return, 1-3
FORMULA.QUARTILEINC: Returns the quartile (each of four equal groups) for a given set of data. QUARTILE.INC can return minimum value, first quartile, second quartile, third quartile, and max value. Starting with Excel 2010, the QUARTILE.INC function replaces the QUARTILE function with the same behavior
FORMULA.QUARTILEINC-OPT: array:A reference containing data to analyze;quart:The quartile value to return, 1-3
FORMULA.RANKAVG: Returns the rank of a number against a list of other other numeric values. When values contain duplicates, the RANK.AVG function will assign an average rank to each set of duplicates
FORMULA.RANKAVG-OPT: number:The number to rank;ref:An array that contains the numbers to rank against;order:Rank ascending or descending. Default is zero
FORMULA.RANKEQ: Returns the rank of a number against a list of other other numeric values. When values contain duplicates, RANK.EQ will assign the higher rank to each set of duplicates
FORMULA.RANKEQ-OPT: number:The number to rank;ref:An array that contains the numbers to rank against;order:Rank ascending or descending. Default is zero
FORMULA.RSQ: Returns the square of the Pearson product moment correlation coefficient through data points in known_y's and known_x's. For more information, see the PEARSON function. The r-squared value can be interpreted as the proportion of the variance in y attributable to the variance in x
FORMULA.RSQ-OPT: known_ys:An array or range of data points;known_xs:An array or range of data points
FORMULA.SKEW: Returns the skewness of a distribution, which is a measure of symmetry. A positive result indicates a distribution that tails off to the right. A negative result indicates a distribution that tails off to the left
FORMULA.SKEW-OPT: number1:A range or reference that contains numeric values;number2:A range or reference that contains numeric values
FORMULA.SKEWP: Returns the skewness of a distribution, which is a measure of symmetry. A positive result indicates a distribution that tails off to the right. A negative result indicates a distribution that tails off to the left
FORMULA.SKEWP-OPT: number1:A range or reference that contains numeric values;number2:A range or reference that contains numeric values
FORMULA.SLOPE: Returns the slope of a regression line based on known y values and known x values. A regression line is a "best fit" line based on known data points
FORMULA.SLOPE-OPT: known_ys:An array or range of numeric data points (dependent values);known_xs:An array or range of numeric data points (independent values)
FORMULA.SMALL: Returns a numeric value based on its position in a list when sorted by value in ascending order. In other words, SMALL can return the "nth smallest" value (1st smallest value, 2nd smallest value, 3rd smallest value, etc.) from a set of numeric data
FORMULA.SMALL-OPT: array:An array or range of numeric values;k:Position as an integer, where 1 corresponds to the smallest value
FORMULA.STANDARDIZE: Returns a normalized value (z-score) based on the mean and standard deviation
FORMULA.STANDARDIZE-OPT: x:The value to normalize;mean:The arithmetic mean of the distribution;standard_dev:The standard deviation of the distribution
FORMULA.STDEVA: Calculates standard deviation for a sample of data. Unlike the STDEV function, STDEVA will evaluate text and logicals that appear in references. To calculate standard deviation for an entire population, use STDEVPA or STDEV.P.
FORMULA.STDEVA-OPT: number1:First number or reference in the sample;number2:Second number or reference
FORMULA.STDEVP: Calculates the standard deviation for data that represents a population. STDEVP has been replaced with a newer function called STDEV.P, which has the same behavior
FORMULA.STDEVP-OPT: number1:First number or reference in the sample;number2:Second number or reference
FORMULA.STDEVPA: Calculates the standard deviation for an entire population. Unlike the STDEVP function, STDEVPA evaluates text and logicals that appear in references. To calculate standard deviation for a sample, use STDEVA or STDEV.S
FORMULA.STDEVPA-OPT: number1:First number or reference in the sample;number2:Second number or reference
FORMULA.STDEVS: Calculates the standard deviation for a sample set of data. STDEV.S replaces the older STDEV function, with the same behavior
FORMULA.STDEVS-OPT: number1:First number or reference in the sample;number2:Second number or reference
FORMULA.STEYX: Returns the standard error of the predicted y-value for each x in the regression. The standard error is a measure of the amount of error in the prediction of y for an individual x
FORMULA.STEYX-OPT: known_ys:An array or range of numeric data points (dependent values);known_xs:An array or range of numeric data points (independent values)
FORMULA.TDIST: Returns the Percentage Points (probability) for the Student t-distribution where a numeric value (x) is a calculated value of t for which the Percentage Points are to be computed. The t-distribution is used in the hypothesis testing of small sample data sets. Use this function in place of a table of critical values for the t-distribution
FORMULA.TDIST-OPT: x:The numeric value at which to evaluate the distribution;deg_freedom:An integer indicating the number of degrees of freedom;tails:Specifies the number of distribution tails to return. If Tails = 1, TDIST returns the one-tailed distribution. If Tails = 2, TDIST returns the two-tailed distribution
FORMULA.TINV: Returns the two-tailed inverse of the Student's t-distribution.
FORMULA.TINV-OPT: probability:The probability associated with the two-tailed Student's t-distribution;deg_freedom:The number of degrees of freedom with which to characterize the distribution
FORMULA.TRIMMEAN: Calculates mean (average) while excluding outliers. The number of data points to exclude is provided as a percentage
FORMULA.TRIMMEAN-OPT: array:Values to trim and average;percent:The number of data points to exclude from the calculation
FORMULA.VARA: Estimates the variance of a sample of data. Unlike the VAR function, the VARA function evaluates text values and logicals in references
FORMULA.VARA-OPT: number1:First number or reference in the sample;number2:Second number or reference
FORMULA.VARP: Calculates the variance of an entire population of data. If data represents a sample, use the VAR function or the newer VAR.S function. VARP ignores text values and logicals in references
FORMULA.VARP-OPT: number1:First number or reference in the sample;number2:Second number or reference
FORMULA.VARPA: Computes the variance of for a population of data. Unlike the VARP function, the VARPA function evaluates text values and logicals in references
FORMULA.VARPA-OPT: number1:First number or reference in the sample;number2:Second number or reference
FORMULA.VARS: Returns the variance of a sample. If data represents the entire population, use the VAR.P function. VAR.S ignores text values and logicals in references
FORMULA.VARS-OPT: number1:First number or reference in the sample;number2:Second number or reference
FORMULA.WEIBULLDIST: Returns the Weibull distribution. Use this distribution in reliability analysis, such as calculating a device's mean time to failure
FORMULA.WEIBULLDIST-OPT: x:The value at which to evaluate the function;alpha:A parameter to the distribution;beta:A parameter to the distribution;Cumulative:Determines the form of the function
FORMULA.ZTEST: Returns the one-tailed probability-value of a z-test. For a given hypothesized population mean, μ0, ZTEST returns the probability that the sample mean would be greater than the average of observations in the data set (array) — that is, the observed sample mean
FORMULA.ZTEST-OPT: array:The array or range of data against which to test x;x:The value to test
FORMULA.CHAR: Returns a character when given a valid character code. CHAR can be used to specify characters that are hard to enter in a formula. For example, CHAR(10) returns a line break on Windows, and CHAR(13) returns a line break on the Mac.
FORMULA.CLEAN: Takes a text string and returns text that has been "cleaned" of line breaks and other non-printable characters.
FORMULA.CODE: Returns a numeric code for a given character.  For example, CODE("a") returns the code 97. The CODE function can be used to figure out numeric codes supplied to the CHAR function.
FORMULA.CODE-OPT: text:The text for which you want a numeric code
FORMULA.CONCATENATE: Concatenates (joins) join up to 30 text items together and returns the result as text
FORMULA.CONCATENATE-OPT: text1:first text value;text2:second text value;text3:third text value
FORMULA.EXACT: Compares two text strings, taking into account upper and lower case characters, and returns TRUE if they are the same, and FALSE if not. EXACT is case-sensitive.
FORMULA.EXACT-OPT: text1:first text to compare;text2:second text to compare
FORMULA.FIND: Finds one text string (find_text) within another text string (within_text), and returns the number of the starting position of find_text, from the first character of within_text. You can also use SEARCH to find one text string within another, but unlike SEARCH, FIND is case sensitive and doesn't allow wildcard characters.
FORMULA.FIND-OPT: find_text:The text to find;within_text:The text to search within;start_num:Starting position in the text to search
FORMULA.LEFT: Returns a Variant (String) containing a specified number of characters from the left side of a string.
FORMULA.LEFT-OPT: text:The text from which to extract characters;num_chars:The number of characters to extract, starting on the left side of text. Default = 1
FORMULA.LEN: Returns the number of characters in a text string
FORMULA.LEN-OPT: text:The text for which to calculate length
FORMULA.LOWER: Converts all uppercase letters in a text string to lowercase.
FORMULA.MID: Returns a Variant (String) containing a specified number of characters from a string.
FORMULA.MID-OPT: text:The text to extract from;start_num:The location of the first character to extract;num_chars:The number of characters to extract
FORMULA.NUMBERVALUE: Converts text to a number, in a locale-independent way.
FORMULA.NUMBERVALUE-OPT: text:The text to convert to a number;decimal_separator:The character for decimal values;group_separator:The character for grouping by thousands
FORMULA.PROPER: Capitalizes the first letter in a text string and any other letters in text that follow any character other than a letter. Converts all other letters to lowercase letters.
FORMULA.REGEXEXTRACT: Extracts substrings that match a regular expression.
FORMULA.REGEXEXTRACT-OPT: text:text to modify;expression:The first part of text that matches this expression will be returned
FORMULA.REGEXMATCH: Indicates whether part of a text matches a regular expression.
FORMULA.REGEXMATCH-OPT: text:text to modify;expression:The first part of text that matches this expression will be returned
FORMULA.REGEXREPLACE: Replaces part of a text string with a different string using regular expressions.
FORMULA.REGEXREPLACE-OPT: text:text to modify;expression:The first part of text that matches this expression will be returned;replace:text to replace
FORMULA.REPLACE: Replaces part of a text string, based on the specified number of characters, with another text string.
FORMULA.REPLACE-OPT: old_text:The text to replace;start_num:The starting location in the text to search;num_chars:The number of characters to replace;new_text:The text to replace old_text with
FORMULA.REPT: Repeats the text a specified number of times. Use REPEAT to fill a cell with a repeated text string a specified number of times.
FORMULA.REPT-OPT: text:The text to repeat;number_times:The number of times to repeat text
FORMULA.RIGHT: Returns a Variant (String) containing a specified number of characters from the right side of a string.
FORMULA.RIGHT-OPT: text:The text from which to extract characters;num_chars:The number of characters to extract, starting on the right side of text. Default = 1
FORMULA.ROMAN: Converts an arabic numeral to roman, as text.
FORMULA.SEARCH: Returns the location of one text string inside another. SEARCH returns the position of the first character of find_text inside within_text. Unlike FIND, SEARCH allows wildcards, and is not case-sensitive.
FORMULA.SEARCH-OPT: find_text:The text to find;within_text:The text to search within;start_num:Starting position in the text to search. Optional, defaults to 1
FORMULA.SPLIT: Returns a zero-based, one-dimensional array containing a specified number of substrings.
FORMULA.SPLIT-OPT: text:Text to cut;delimiter:Character used to separate substrings
FORMULA.SUBSTITUTE: Substitutes new_text for old_text in a text string. Use SUBSTITUTE when you want to replace specific text in a text string; use REPLACE when you want to replace any text that occurs in a specific location in a text string.
FORMULA.SUBSTITUTE-OPT: text:The text to change;old_text:The text to replace;new_text:The text to replace with;instance:The instance to replace. If not supplied, all instances are replaced.
FORMULA.T: Returns the text to which the value argument refers.
FORMULA.TRIM: Removes all spaces from text except for single spaces between words. Use TRIM on text that you have received from another application that may have irregular spacing.
FORMULA.UNICHAR: Returns the Unicode character that is referenced by the given numeric value.
FORMULA.UNICODE: Returns the number (code point) corresponding to the first character of the text.
